@NikolajBjorner is there any way of knowing more precisely which strings are accepted for a given parameter, or should they all just be typed as "string"?

Also, is there any way to get the default values for parameters? A way of getting the current value for the given context would be sufficient, since you can just make a context without setting any parameters and then read off the values for that context.

---

The fact that it has to be invoked at runtime rather than parsed from source means it will add another step to the build process, but we do have a thing we can invoke after calling `build:wasm`, so:

```js
'use strict';

(async () => {
  let mod = await require('./build/z3-built.js')();
  let ctx = mod._Z3_mk_context();
  let paramDescriptors = mod._Z3_get_global_param_descrs(ctx);
  mod._Z3_param_descrs_inc_ref(ctx, paramDescriptors);

  let configType = 'type ConfigParams = {';
  let size = mod._Z3_param_descrs_size(ctx, paramDescriptors);
  for (let i = 0; i < size; ++i) {
    let nameSymbol = mod._Z3_param_descrs_get_name(ctx, paramDescriptors, i);
    let name = mod.UTF8ToString(mod._Z3_get_symbol_string(ctx, nameSymbol));
    let comment = mod.UTF8ToString(mod._Z3_param_descrs_get_documentation(ctx, paramDescriptors, nameSymbol));
    configType += `\n  ${name}: string, // ${comment}`
  }
  configType += `\n};`;

  console.log(configType);
  mod.PThread.terminateAllThreads();
})().catch(e => {
  console.error(e);
  process.exit(1);
});
```
produces
```ts
type ConfigParams = {
  proof: string, // proof generation, it must be enabled when the Z3 context is created
  smtlib2_compliant: string, // enable/disable SMT-LIB 2.0 compliance
