Let's see if we can dissect what's going on in these tests.

1) 2 different objectives: LeastSquares and LogLikelihood. If LS is used both an x and a y are passed, with LL only x is passed.
2) A few different minimizers are used
3) Sometimes constraints are used, but not all minimizers can deal with those.
4) The resulting FitResults have different attributes/values in the end.

Although 1 and 2+3 are orthogonal (i.e. could be separate `parametrize` calls), but 4 will be different for all combinations.

Idea 1: make a big table:
```python
@pytest.mark.parametrize('fit_kwargs, param_values, param_std, gof_values', [
    (
       {'x': ..., 'y': ..., 'objective': LeastSquares, 'minimizer': ..., 'constraints': ...}
       {'a': ..., 'b': ...}, {'a': ..., 'b': ...}
       {'r_squared': 0.99, ...}
    ),
    .
    .
    .
])
def test_everything(...):
```
Pro: minimal number of tests, easy
Con: Maximum number of parametrizations, missing combinations.

Idea 2: Separate out the special cases: LogLikelihood, and constraints.
```python
MINIMIZERS = subclasses(BaseMinimizer)  # https://github.com/tBuLi/symfit/blob/ecc567a1e75092dc3c94cecb0b44c132dbab7f4e/tests/test_minimizers.py#L63
CONSTR_MINIMIZERS = subclasses(ConstrainedMinimizer)

@pytest.mark.parametrize('minimizer', 
    MINIMIZERS
)
def test_least_sq_no_constraint(minimizer):
    objective = LeastSquares
    expected = {'a': 3, 'b': 2}
    expected_std = {'a': ..., 'b': ...}
    expected_gof = {'r_squared': 0.99, ...}
    fit_kwargs = dict(objective=objective, minimizer=minimizer, x=..., y=...)
    _run_test(fit_kwargs, expected, expected_std, expected_gof)

@pytest.mark.parametrize('minimizer', 
    CONSTR_MINIMIZERS
)
def test_least_sq_constraint(minimizer):
    objective = LeastSquares
    expected = {'a': ..., 'b': ...}
    expected_std = {'a': ..., 'b': ...}
    expected_gof = {'r_squared': 0.99, ...}
    fit_kwargs = dict(objective=objective, minimizer=minimizer, x=..., y=..., constraints=...)
    _run_test(fit_kwargs, expected, expected_std, expected_gof)

@pytest.mark.parametrize('minimizer', 
    MINIMIZERS
)
def test_likelihood_no_constr(minimizer):
    objective = LogLikelihood
    expected = {'a': ..., 'b': ...}
    expected_std = {'a': ..., 'b': ...}
    expected_gof = {...}
    fit_kwargs = dict(objective=objective, minimizer=minimizer, x=..., y=..., constraints=...)
    _run_test(fit_kwargs, expected, expected_std, expected_gof)

# etc, etc

def _run_test(fit_kwargs, expected, expected_std, expected_gof):
    fit = Fit(**fit_kwargs)
    ... # assert all the things!
```
CON: many different tests, some code duplication
PRO: probably best coverage of all different cases, minimal duplication of data/cases


At the moment I think idea 2 has my preference. What do you think?

